  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The study on the structural modeling of the 2019-novel coronavirus spike protein has garnered significant attention, with a total of 511 citations and 24 mentions across various platforms. This preprint has successfully transferred to a peer-reviewed publication, indicating a robust academic impact and widespread adoption in related research fields.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The research conducted by Jaimes et al. has made an impactful contribution to the understanding of the nCoV spike protein, revealing how a proteolytically-sensitive activation loop distinguishes it from SARS-CoV and related SARS-like coronaviruses. Since its early sharing on bioRxiv, the study has been cited 511 times, illustrating the high level of interest and relevance in the scientific community. Additionally, it has been referenced in a variety of venues, indicating its interdisciplinary appeal and the broad application of its findings across different aspects of virology and structural biology.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This preprint, which has now been formally published, highlights the authors' commitment to open science practices by generating immediate community engagement prior to its final publication. The metrics following the peer-reviewed release confirm that the combined discourse surrounding both the preprint and the final publication is substantial, with an impressive 505 citations registered for the published version alone. This suggests that the research has had a direct impact on ongoing studies into coronavirus structure and function, particularly during a time of urgent global concern regarding viral outbreaks.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Moreover, the findings are further amplified by the diverse geographical footprint of its citations, which includes contributions from the United States, the United Kingdom, Iran, Brazil, and India. This international acknowledgment underscores the study's relevance and the collaborative nature of contemporary virological research. In addition, the absence of risk and credibility alerts positions this work as a credible and reliable resource in a field where scrutiny and replication are paramount.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Overall, the work of Jaimes and colleagues exemplifies a significant scholarly advancement in our understanding of COVID-19's underlying mechanisms, contributing fundamentally to future research on SARS-like coronaviruses and enhancing the collective knowledge needed to address pandemic challenges. The rise in citations and the transition to formal publication underscore the study's role as a foundational piece of research in virology.</p>",
